In recent years, essential oils (EOs) of aromatic plants species have attracted great attention as natural products that can effectively act as insecticides and repellents against insect pests [
 25; 
 26; 
 27; 
 28; 
 29]. Moreover, since EOs usually have a low toxicity to mammals [
 30], and high biodegradability, they are regarded as very promising substances for the formulation of low-toxic, eco-friendly pest control products [
 31].The common green bottle fly 
 Lucilia sericata (Meigen) (Diptera Calliphoridae) (
 Fig 1) is a common blowfly frequently found in synanthropic and natural ecosystems in most areas of the world and, along with 
 L. 
 cuprina (Wied.), and 
 L. 
 caesar (L.), it is a common cause of human and animal cutaneous myiasis [
 32; 
 33].
